Put the @water{750%ml}, @chicken stock powder{1} and @saffron{1%pinch} into a large #saucepan{} and place on medium-low heat. Stir to dissolve the stock. Cut the @medium tomato{2} into wedges (eight per tomato). Halve, peel and thinly slice the @echalion shallot{1} into thin half moons. Finely chop the @flat leaf parsley{1%bunch} (stalks and all).

Pop the tomato wedges onto a lined #baking tray{}. Drizzle on a splash of @olive oil{for roasting}, the @balsamic vinegar{12%ml} and season with a pinch of @salt{pinch}. Roast on the top shelf of your oven for ~{20%minutes}, then remove and keep to one side.

Meanwhile, heat a glug of @olive oil{for the pan} in another large saucepan over medium heat. While it heats up, brown the @diced chicken thigh{260%g} in the pan for ~{5%minutes} and then add the shallot. Cook until the shallot has softened, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Add the @Arborio rice{175%g} to the pan. Stir to coat the rice in oil and then add a ladleful of stock. Stir continually until the stock has been absorbed by the rice. Continue this process until all of the stock is used. This should take about ~{20%minutes}.

> TIP: Taste your rice, add a splash more hot water and cook for another minute or 
> so if it is still a bit firm.

In between stirring, zest the @lemon{1/2} and mix with the parsley. This is your gremolata. Squeeze the lemon juice into a large #bowl{} with the @olive oil{for the dressing} and the @honey{15%g}. Toss the @baby leaf mix{50%g} in the dressing just before serving. When your risotto is cooked, remove from the heat and mix in the @grated hard Italian style cheese{40%g} and a knob of @?butter{some}. Taste and add some @salt{} and @pepper{} if required.

Share the risotto between your bowls, pop the tomato wedges on top. Sprinkle over the gremolata. Serve the baby leaf mix alongside. Eat without delay!

> Risotto does not like sitting around. Enjoy!